<TEXT>
villagers in southern lebanon got their 
wish the irish government has decided to keep its 750man 
batallion in the united nations peacekeeping forces here 
the government in dublin had been reconsidering the irish 
battalions presence in lebanon because four of its soldiers had 
been killed and one wounded in three attacks in the past three 
months three of them were killed by a landmine march 21 
we greatly need the irish contingent in south lebanon said 
abbas fawaz the mayor of tibnin a town 11 miles north of the 
israeli border 
the estimated 100000 shiite moslems living in 20 hamlets around 
tibnin the irish headquarters enjoy their protection fawaz 
said 
before making the decision the irish cabinet reviewed a report 
by lt gen tadhg oneill chief of staff of the irish army who 
had come here to investigate the landmine explosion march 21 
the cabinet renews irelands commitment every six months and 
the irish political opposition had called for a policy review after 
the deaths the fourth death occurred earlier 
our presence here is very vital to the security of the area 
and to the locals who depend on our humanitarian aide said lt 
col pat mcmahon commander of the irish contingent in the united 
nations interim force in lebanon unifil 
on march 30 hundreds of tebnins 5000 residents participated 
in a memorial ceremony for the three irish soldiers killed by the 
landmine 
the irish contingent lives among its people in the south 
said one of the banners at the ceremony aggression against it is 
aggression on the southerners 
the un peacekeeping force made up of 5800 personnel from 
nine nations has monitored a narrow strip of 65towns and villages 
in south lebanon since march 1985 
the population in the forces area of operation increased from 
about 50000 when the force first arrived to about a half million 
people today 
before unifil came to south lebanon the area was a free 
terrain to militiamen and terrorists who spread fear and death 
everywhere said fawaz 64 who has been mayor for 20 years 
now everyone is moving around here peacefully and freely 
thanks to the irish battalion 
an irish sergeant about to be moved out on routine rotation said 
he was leaving with mixed feelings 
there are a lot of poor people here who are in great need of 
our humanitarian work which is worth risking my life for said 
the sergeant who could not allow his name to be used because of 
standing regulations 
an irish major at headquarters in tebnin said it would be a 
fire zone without us 
when the irish battalion first came here the villagers did 
not have any electricity and had shortages of water he said 
but we helped them and now they are confident in their future 
because of us 
the irish battalion has lost 30 soldiers in attacks by various 
groups over the years 
investigations were still under way to determine who planted the 
landmine that exploded under a unifil jeep near haddatha on march 
21 and killed the three soldiers lt col patrick hayes said 
the other two recent attacks were carried out by the 
israelibacked south lebanon army sla militia which controls a 
narrow strip of lebanese territory that israel refers to as its 
security zone 
israel maintained the zone when it pulled out the bulk of its 
invading army from south lebanon in the summer of 1985 ending a 
threeyear occupation 
the terrain which extends from the mediterranean sea in the 
west to the slopes of snowpeaked mount hermon in the east serves 
as a buffer against crossborder infiltrations by palestinian 
guerrillas into northern israeli settlements 
col mcmahon blamed israel for the south lebanon army attacks on 
the irish battalion he said such hostilities were due to the 
lack of control from the israeli army command on the sla 
militiamen 
hassan fawaz the son of tebnins mayor who owns a gift shop 
near the irish battalion headquarters said tebnin residents 
notify the irish command about the possibility of any attack on 
them that we come to know of 
the younger fawaz stressed the economic value that the irish 
battalion represents to the area the troops spend at least 
500000 annually on souvenirs and goods they buy dutyfree from 
local stores 
</TEXT>
