<TEXT>
aerosol makers in european economic 
community nations have agreed to sharply reduce the use of 
chemicals that harm the earths protective ozone layer the eec 
commission has announced 
the commission said the federation of european aerosol 
manufacturers will voluntarily reduce the use of 
chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs in aerosol cans by 90 percent by dec 
31 1990 
since the use of cfcs in aerosols accounts for about 45 
percent of the total use of cfcs in the community we will be 
achieving with this voluntary agreement a higher reduction than 
the 20 percent reduction required under the 1987 montreal 
protocol the commission said in a statement thursday 
the montreal treaty signed by 40 nations is aimed at lowering 
the use of chlorofluorocarbons which have been blamed for the 
deterioration of the ozone layer that protects the earth from the 
cancercausing effects of ultraviolet rays and increases the 
greenhouse effect or heating of the environment 
exempted from the voluntary accord with the eec commission 
however are aerosols used in electronics and pharmaceuticals and 
some specialized industrial uses the eec commission said 
it said it will seek similar accords with other trade groups 
that use cfcs in their industries such as makers of refrigerators 
air conditioners solvents and foam plastics 
when released into the environment cfcs rise into stratosphere 
where ultraviolet rays break them up releasing chlorine and bromine 
atoms that can keep destroying the ozone layer for years 
</TEXT>
