<TEXT>
the spread of aidsvirus infections in the united 
states could trigger dramatic increases in tuberculosis cases 
according to federal health officials 
the national centers for disease control responding to an 
increasing link between aids and tuberculosis urged doctors 
thursday to give tb tests to patients infected with the aids virus 
and to make aids testing available to tb patients 
the number of the nations 20000 annual tuberculosis patients 
who are also infected with the aids virus is unknown but one study 
cited by the cdc matching reported tb cases with aids cases in 43 
states found that 4 percent of aids patients also were listed as 
tb patients 
the cdc also reported thursday that the focus of aids in the 
united states is shifting away from the northeast as more and more 
cases are showing up in smaller cities 
only 32 percent of the nations aids cases in 1988 were reported 
from new york new jersey and pennsylvania compared with 54 
percent four years earlier 
its moving outside of the major metropolitan areas and 
outside the northeast said cdc aids specialist dr jeannette 
stehrgreen noting that the proportion of cases in urban areas 
under 500000 population increased from 12 percent in pre1986 
years to 19 percent in 1988 
tuberculosis is one of a number of opportunistic infections 
which can prey on the weakened immune systems of aids patients and 
can serve as an early indicator of the disease 
but tuberculosis is one of the few infections associated with 
hiv thats transmissible by the airborne route so there are 
public health implications here said dr carol a ciesielski a 
cdc tuberculosis specialist 
the cdc in a report from its advisory committee for the 
elimination of tuberculosis said all patients diagnosed with 
tuberculosis should be offered aids testing and counseling 
likewise aidsinfected persons should be given tuberculosis tests 
the reason ciesielski said is that tb unlike many infections 
that can plague aids patients is curable and preventable by 
testing early you can give them medicine to prevent them 
developing it preventing a new case from occurring 
tuberculosis a bacterial infection of the lungs can be cured 
or prevented in most cases with drugs studies have suggested that 
a latent infection with tb bacteria may often progress to 
clinical tb early in the course of a persons infection with the 
aids virus the cdc said 
in some areas the link between tb and aids can be high a 
florida study found that 10 percent of aids patients were also tb 
patients a study at a new jersey hospital found a connection in 21 
percent the cdc said 
minority populations in some highaids areas have been at 
particular risk of aidsassociated tb the cdc said studies in 
new york city florida and newark nj found that blacks and 
hispanics accounted for more than 80 percent of the tbaids cases 
in its report thursday on the eight years since aids was first 
reported the cdc said the rate of increase in the number of 
documented aids cases has declined 
the number of aids cases as compared with the year before shot 
up 215 percent between 1982 and 1983 since then the increase has 
slowed up 117 percent in 1984 84 percent in 1985 60 percent in 
1986 60 percent again in 1987 and 34 percent last year when 
32311 cases were reported said stehrgreen chief of the cdcs 
aids reporting and analysis section 
in the latest monthly count from the cdc the nation has 
reported 90990 aids cases and 52435 of those patients or 58 
percent have died 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

