<DOCNO> AP890414-0078 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
coronary bypass surgery may not be the best 
solution for everybody but it still offers greater benefits to 
nearly all heartdisease patients than drugs and diet alone 
according to a study published today 
if youre an 80yearold who isnt terribly active but want 
to see your grandkids grow up medical treatment may be 
sufficient said dr robert califf of the duke university medical 
center and principal author of the study 
but if youre an 80yearold who enjoys playing golf and other 
exercise then surgery may very well be worth it he said 
thursday in a telephone interview from his office in durham nc 
blockages of the coronary arteries lead to heart attacks which 
claim about 500000 victims each year and are the leading cause of 
death in the united states 
debate has raged within the medical community in recent years 
over the most efficient and costeffective manner of treatment 
this message is that while bypass leads to a better outcome 
were not prescribing surgery for every patient with blocked 
arteries califf said 
califf said the new research published in todays editions of 
the journal of the american medical association better defines the 
relative benefits and risks giving doctors and patients more 
information on which to base a decision 
currently about half of all new cases of heart disease are 
treated with drugs and diet and lifestyle management which usually 
involves weight loss exercise and lowering such risk factors as 
cholesterol intake and stress 
treatment of the remaining cases is split about evenly between 
coronary bypass a procedure in which doctors surgically attach new 
blood vessels to improve blood flow and angioplasty which 
involves surgical insertion of a balloon to widen narrowed arteries 
the scientists limited the study group to 5809 coronary disease 
patients who received either medical treatment 2847 or bypass 
surgery 2962 between 1969 and 1984 
the study found that the greater benefits afforded by coronary 
bypass surgery applied across the spectrum of patients regardless 
of age or degree of heart dysfunction and that both the oneyear 
and fiveyear survival rates after surgical treatment climbed 
dramatically between 1970 and 1980 
but califf said researchers determined that all methods of 
treating coronary disease had improved so much in the 15year 
period that bypass surgery ultimately may be the best course of 
treatment only for those patients with the most severe coronary 
blockages 
coronary bypass procedures cost about 30000 compared to an 
absolute maximum of several thousand dollars for drug diet and 
lifestyle therapy 
the study did not measure the costeffectiveness of the two 
treatments although califf is involved in several of a number of 
ongoing studies that will do so 
the study also did not examine angioplasty average cost 
12000 as an alternative and in an editorial in the same issue 
dr j willis hurst suggested the time had come for a comparative 
study including angioplasty 
just as general agreement is reached regarding the value of 
bypass surgery compared with medical management we now must 
consider the indications for coronary angioplasty said hurst of 
the emory university school of medicine in atlanta 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

