<DOCNO> AP890414-0093 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a gene that is thought to be responsible for 
the development of colon cancer has been identified by researchers 
in a study published today in the journal science researchers 
from maryland texas and utah reported that a gene called p53 tends 
to be found in a mutated form in colon cancer tumors 
the discovery eventually could lead to specific tests to detect 
the disease before other symptoms occur and while the cancer is 
still curable the study said 
the researchers said they also found that almost all colon 
cancers lose additional genetic material as the tumors progress 
several genetic changes are probably required for the 
development of these cancers said bert vogelstein an associate 
professor at johns hopkins oncology center in baltimore 
the report said that 53 of 56 colon tumors excised by surgery 
and analyzed showed the loss of genetic material and that patients 
with the most genetic changes were those most likely to experience 
a return of their colon cancer 
the study said the p53 gene is a suppressor gene that can 
inhibit tumor growth normal cells have two such genes colon 
cancer cells however have no normal copies of the gene one copy 
is lost and the other is mutated 
studies suggest that mutation of suppressor genes remove part of 
the bodys resistance to tumor growth 
colon cancer is diagnosed in 147000 people a year in the united 
states and about 61000 die of the disease it ranks second in 
frequency and death among the types of cancers 
the research for the report was performed at johns hopkins the 
university of utah and at md anderson hospital and the baylor 
college of medicine in houston 
science is the journal of the american association for the 
advance of science 
</TEXT>
