the agriculture department said friday it has 
approved the first field test of a genetically engineered cotton 
plant that protects itself from destructive insects 
james w glosser administrator of the departments animal and 
plant health inspection service said permission was given to the 
agracetus co middleton wis for testing the new cotton variety 
in starkville miss beginning immediately 
glosser said the testing procedure was reviewed by his agency 
and determined to be well designed and environmentally safe 
the companys scientists inserted a gene into the cotton plant 
from a common soil bacterium bacillus thuringienensis the gene 
produces a protein that is toxic to caterpillartype insects but 
not to humans mammals or most other insects 
glosser said if the cotton performs as the company hopes it 
would mean the plants are protected against such pests as the 
bollworm tobacco budworm and armyworm the department estimates 
these pests cost us cotton producers about 128 million in 1988 
including lost yields and costs of insecticides 
</TEXT>
