<TEXT>
the government reported friday that business 
inventories rose 05 percent in february while sales fell 09 
percent a combination that analysts said could point toward 
production cutbacks if it continues 
inventories held on shelves and backlots climbed to a seasonally 
adjusted 7636 billion in february following a 08 percent 
increase in january the commerce department reported 
sales meanwhile dropped to a seasonally adjusted 5073 
billion in february after rising 11 percent in the previous month 
the decline was the first since sales fell 02 percent in november 
1987 the month after the stock market crash and marked the 
steepest drop in more than two years 
februarys report was consistent with a host of other 
indications that economic growth is slowing as the record peacetime 
expansion extends into its seventh year 
if increases in inventories are not accompanied by rising sales 
analysts say the result could be production cutbacks that hold down 
economic growth 
robert g dederick chief economist for northern trust co in 
chicago said the inventory buildup isnt alarming yet but 
unless we can get some sales they are quickly going to be at a 
disturbing level 
the accumulation rate really has been heavy enough that we 
could develop excesses rather quickly if sales did soften 
dederick said i view this as a danger area 
februarys business activity produced an increase in the ratio 
of inventories to sales to 151 to 1 meaning it would take 151 
months to exhaust inventories at februarys sales pace the ratio 
had been 148 to 1 in january 
februarys increase in inventories was led by a 08 percent rise 
in stocks held by retailers followed by a 05 percent gain in 
manufacturer inventories and a 02 percent gain at the wholesale 
level 
in the retail category stockpiles of unsold cars were up 04 
percent as sales declined 24 percent auto sales have been weak 
this year and carmakers are offering new incentive programs in 
hopes of luring more people to dealerships 
februarys decline in business sales included a 17 percent drop 
in manufacturer sales a 06 percent drop in retail sales and a 
virtually unchanged level of sales activity for wholesalers 
analysts have blamed februarys poor sales figures on harsh 
weather that followed a warmweather surge in january marchs 
advance report on retail sales showed purchases edged up 01 
percent 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

