<DOCNO> AP890414-0145 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the us merchandise trade deficit widened 
sharply in february the government said friday bolstering 
economists belief that improvement in the nations trade 
performance is fizzling 
the commerce department said the monthly seasonally adjusted 
deficit swelled 209 percent to 105 billion up from a revised 
868 billion in january the deterioration reflected a 53 percent 
increase in imports which swamped a slight 06 percent improvement 
in sales of us goods abroad 
the trade gap for the first two months of the year is running at 
an annual rate of 115 billion scarcely below the 11976 billion 
deficit for all 1988 
commerce secretary robert mosbacher said i continue to be 
encouraged that the annual deficit will show further improvement in 
1989 but most private economists disagree 
the rise in oil prices to the 20abarrel level will inflate 
imports while the strength of the dollar will make the price of 
american goods more expensive discouraging export sales they say 
trade fizzled some time ago and this fits in with the theme 
that were still on an unacceptably high plateau said robert 
dederick chief economist at northern trust co in chicago 
the good news is that after worsening in the fourth quarter 
the trade deficit seems to have narrowed a bit but the bad news is 
that still leaves us no better off than last spring he said 
a dramatic 21 percent decline in the trade gap last year from a 
peak of 1521 billion in 1987 accounted for nearly half of 
overall economic growth as measured by the gross national product 
the bush administration is counting on further trade improvement to 
bolster the economy and help it meet its pledges to reduce the 
federal budget deficit without new taxes 
the february performance reflected a 53 percent jump in 
imports which rose to a seasonally adjusted 394 billion the 
higher figure included increases of 10 billion in sales of 
foreign capital goods to businesses and 800 million in purchases 
of foreign cars 
its clear that major improvement in trade continues to be 
held captive by our addiction to imports said economist jerry 
jasinowski of the national association of manufacturers the us 
continues to suck in industrial materials parts and 
equipment 
