<TEXT>
about 60 miles south of valdez ed 
morris walks a sad beat on beautiful but hauntingly empty green 
island 
morris is a regular visitor to this and other oilstained 
islands in prince william sound his job is to collect dead animals 
and birds and occasionally a halfdead sea gull or otter so mired 
in oily goo that it cant float or fly 
since he began the job eight days ago hes recovered 100 dead 
creatures 12 maybe 15 live ones that is a small fraction of the 
thousands that have died or been contaminated since the exxon 
valdez went aground three weeks ago spewing 101 million gallons 
of oil into sounds bountiful marine habitat 
morris rides to the unpopulated islands in an orange zodiak 
rubber boat watching both the edge and top of the shoreline 
the dead ones are usually up here in the oily grass he 
says pointing to the hightide mark of greasy seaweed they just 
roll up there with the tide 
the living ones are down by the waters edge they stay there 
in case they feel threatened so they can try to get away in the 
water he says 
if they swim away it will mean death their fur and feathers 
are coated with oil they can no longer float or keep their body 
warmth 
animals still living are flown to valdez where they are cleaned 
and rehabilitated the dead ones are collected by a shuttle 
boat 
its all pretty sickening says morris a cordova resident 
who normally fishes for salmon in the adjacent oilfouled waters of 
knight island 
morris was wintering in california when he heard about the 
spill he hurried home i wanted to take care of whatever had to 
be taken care of he says 
so morris was hired by veco a subcontractor of exxon helping to 
conduct the cleanup he is one of the hundreds signed on during the 
employment boom created by the spill 
the money at a base wage of 1669 an hour is good and it is 
steady jobs are likely to last a long time in the aftermath of the 
spill morris is doing his part but he doesnt like what he sees 
on the quiet shorelines 
i dont enjoy it but somebodys got to do it i guess he 
says 
