the events at the historic fort west of el reno constitute the 
largest authentic reenactment in the state it is a prelude to 
events in guthrie where the centennial of the land rush will be 
observed the following weekend 
a century ago thousands of settlers gathered in camps around 
the unassigned lands in the days before the run collecting 
supplies and girding for a mad dash for land 
about 2500 soldiers were stationed in and around the 2 million 
acres of the unassigned lands in what is now central oklahoma 
their job was to help federal marshals keep the peace and to keep 
out the sooners who tried to sneak in early 
most of the trouble encountered was evicting squatters 
rounding up cattle rustlers timber thieves hunters and notifying 
ranch owners to vacate their cattle prior to april 20 sgt john 
brandt trumpeter of troop l 5th cavalry wrote 
at noon on april 22 1889 the boom of cannon from fort reno and 
gunshots and bugles elsewhere signaled the beginning of the run for 
more than 40000 settlers 
there were sounds of a mighty roar and cheer whips cracking 
and men shouting to their horses said brandt who was stationed 
near purcell one of eight major starting points for the run 
the saddle horses plunged and raced by at top speed the 
lighter vehicles and faster horses stretched out towards the river 
then the slower horses and heavier wagons thundered by 
while there were more than a dozen other land openings through 
lotteries and runs before statehood in 1907 historians say it was 
the first land run that started the inevitable movement toward 
statehood 
