research experiments 
but friedman said the institute of medicine panel came out 
squarely against this idea regarding it as not likely to catch any 
determined cheaters but very likely to lead to interminable 
arguments about the selection and interpretation of research data 
it would inevitably be extremely costly in professional time 
and would pit a new investigative bureaucracy against the 
scientific community he said 
