<TEXT>
pulitzer prizes dont impress national 
advertisers but fourcolor graphics and younger readers do 
newspaper editors were told friday by ad executives who said 
editors must show that newspapers are not dinosaurs but are a 
hot visible advertising medium 
newspapers must spruce up their images and use innovative ad 
campaigns if they want take ad dollars away from television and 
magazines the executives told a session of the american society of 
newspaper editors convention 
robert wehling vice president marketing services at the 
nations second largest advertiser procter amp gamble said surveys 
show that newspaper readers tend to be over 40 whereas advertisers 
want to reach under40 audiences 
magazines he said have better fourcolor printing capability 
and magazines tend to be read more than once newspapers he said 
get thrown out with the next days trash 
newspapers also are cluttered and their ads dont show products 
being used as well as television does wehling said 
most national advertisers see a significant cost 
disadvantage in using newspapers when compared with television 
and magazines he said 
there is simply no compelling reason for national advertisers 
to redirect dollars to the newspaper medium wehling said 
newspapers could help themselves by emphasizing regional ad 
campaigns by giving advertisers better positions and by trying to 
link local and national advertising campaigns wehling said 
he said one bright star for national newspaper advertising has 
