<TEXT>
the 1000ton shippingport reactor vessel 
was rolled off a columbia river barge thursday and headed for its 
final resting place on the hanford nuclear reservation officials 
said 
the cylindrical vessel from the worlds first commercial 
nuclear reactor was cradled on a 320wheel trailer after it was 
rolled off the barge paul bunyan without incident said tom bauman 
a spokesman for the us department of energy 
friday the trailer will be moved about 13 miles and into a 
40foot deep trench where the reactor vessel will be left for 
burial bauman said 
the reactor vessel arrived at the port of benton on wednesday 
completing an 8100mile 44day waterborne journey from the 
shippingport atomic power station about 35 miles northwest of 
pittsburgh 
the station was built by the us atomic energy commission and 
commissioned in 1957 it was operated jointly with duquesne light 
co to provide power for the pittsburgh area 
shut down in 1982 the reactors dismantling and burial has been 
a pilot project for the decommissioning of other aging reactors 
because the reactor is owned by the federal government it was 
slated for burial at hanford 
hanford best known as a site where plutonium is produced for 
nuclear weapons is also the burial ground for the reactor 
compartments from four us navy submarines 
the reactor vessel which federal officials have said is 
lowlevel radioactive waste and not considered very dangerous went 
down the mississippi river into the gulf of mexico through the 
panama canal and up the pacific coast to the mouth of the columbia 
protesters gathered at bridges above the columbia to say they do 
not want the river to become a highway for radioactive waste 
the reactor vessel is 45 feet high and 18 feet across and 
contained the nuclear fuel during operation the fuel was removed 
in 1984 and a nuclear reaction is no longer possible it is filled 
with concrete and placed in a 6inchthick stainless steel box 
</TEXT>
