measured by the emotions generated the minimum 
wage bill now being refined by senatehouse conferees is a 
significant legislative effort a threatened veto by president bush 
adds to that impression 
measured on its potential economic impact on the national 
economy however it may be a far less important piece of 
legislation to some extent it is merely recognizing what already 
has occurred 
in large areas of the country for instance employers long ago 
gave up efforts to hire unskilled help at the minimum wage of 
335 for many months they have been offering considerably more 
even double the minimum 
the 335 wage has been in place for eight years a period 
during which almost every fulltime worker received some sort of 
raise if only to keep pace with inflation in effect the minimum 
wage went backward during this time 
the senate and house bills that have just been passed would 
raise that wage to 455 an hour by october 1 1991 or more than 
two years from now but even then it would hardly match the wages 
available today in many states 
that is not the only reason why the impact might be muted 
another is that 11 states already have higher minimums than the 
federal rate still another is that many companies have the option 
of automating instead of employing 
in fact one of the sturdiest arguments against raising the 
minimum wage rate is the belief that small companies will simply 
eliminate minimum wage jobs and large companies will seek to 
automate such positions out of existence 
further support for the minimum wageminimum impact argument is 
evidence that workers with potential seldom stay at the lowest wage 
anyway usually advancing to higherpaying jobs or quitting 
in spite of this evidence great emotions are generated whenever 
the minimum wage is discussed and sometimes they are justified 
a higher minimum wage costs jobs says the minimum wage 
coalition to save jobs selfdescribed as a broadbased 
organization opposed to any increase in the federal minimum wage 
it also generates inflation the group says 
one of the more disturbing contentions is that the minimum wage 
is promoted as something it is not it cannot improve the lot of 
the poorest workers it is said because minimumwage jobs often go 
to higherincome families 
according to this argument many of the lowest paid positions 
are occupied not by the unskilled but my secondary earners often 
women and teenagers whose incomes merely add to a households 
primary income 
in retailing says economist william dunkelberg 70 percent of 
minimumwage recipients are from families with incomes more than 
200 percent above the poverty level lowincome workers he says 
make up 10 percent of the total 
but while the impact on the economys direction might be almost 
imperceptible and the goal of helping the neediest might be 
missed the bills passed by the house and senate might very well 
have serious impact 
very small businesses are concerned because small increases can 
represent a large percentage of earnings depressed economic areas 
where wages are lower than the minimum would feel a greater impact 
than would stronger regions and businesses everywhere might find 
more paperwork and compliance worries 
but the impact on the economy as a whole isnt likely to be 
impressive and there might be no impact at all if president bush 
does indeed veto the matter before it is enacted 
