<TEXT>
a usiraeli team with 
remotecontrolled yellow submarines the size of sea turtles is 
searching the bottom of the sea of galilee for underwater salt 
wells 
but they also have taken the time to look for remnants of a 
battle between jews and romans in 67 ad when 6700 jews were 
believed to have been killed 
the submarines were brought to israel by us marine scientists 
its the first time we can see for ourselves what the bottom 
of the lake looks like said tom berman director of the kinneret 
laboratory for limnology on galilees northern shore kinneret is 
the hebrew name for the sea of galilee 
project director richard cooper a marine scientist from the 
university of connecticut said submarines are superior to divers 
because they go as deep as 1000 feet and more importanly in this 
case can stay under water for as long as 10 hours 
one recent day aboard the projects control boat anchored a 
little over a mile offshore cooper lowered one submarine equipped 
with a tv camera still camera and strobe light into the lake to 
look for salt water craters 
geologists biologists and marine scientists gathered around a 
small monitor on deck to analyze the tv cameras pictures from the 
rocky bed of the lake which about 140 feet at its deepest point 
the 64squaremile sea of galilee is about 700 feet below sea 
level and is israels major source of fresh water providing nearly 
onethird of the nations supply 
salt levels are now at an acceptable level but might increase if 
water levels drop because of scant rainfall berman said 
data collected by the submarines could help scientists lower the 
lakes salt levels by determining what activates the salt wells 
nobody understands the mechanisms whereby these salt sources 
begin to flow berman said 
scientists also got a closer look at a threefoothigh ridge on 
the lakes bottom indicating recent earthquake activity the sea 
of galilee is part of an active rift valley extending from the 
jordan valley and the dead sea to the red sea in the south 
the 15member crew of the control boat spent one day during the 
twoweek project looking for what they might find from the lake 
battle in 67 ad said shelley wachsmann inspector for underwater 
antiquities in the israel department of antiquities and museums 
the battle took place during the roman conquest of galilee when 
the romans overran the town of migdal on the western shore of the 
lake jews fled in boats the romans pursued them in hastily 
constructed rafts and killed about 6700 in the battle 
one could see the whole lake stained with blood and crammed 
with corpses for not one man escaped wrote the jewish historian 
and soldier flavius josephus who took part in the battle 
wachsmann said the submarines probed several areas in the 
northern part of the lake where initial research indicated boats 
from the battle might have sunk 
the submarines came up with nothing but wachsmann said they 
would be useful tools in future research 
the submarine project is part of a us national oceanic and 
atmospheric administration longterm study comparing large lakes 
around the world including lake victoria and lake malawi in africa 
and the great lakes in the united states 
the submarines are going back to the united states when the 
project ends but the scientists will return next year for further 
studies berman said 
