<TEXT>
lowell jay milken is two years younger than his 
betterknown brother michael he never traded junk bonds he isnt 
michaels righthand man he prefers the background and he faces 
85 fewer charges of committing criminal acts 
friends dispute the perception of lowell milken as the guy in 
the back room hunched over a ledger wearing a green eyeshade 
toiling away for his brother as he was described in a 1988 book 
about milken and drexel the predators ball 
lowell has been very much his own man said martin klein a 
new york lawyer and friend of lowells younger by two years but 
certainly not any less creative or any less dedicated or any less 
hardworking 
but as michael milkens star rose in the late 1970s and 1980s as 
the architect of drexel burnham lambert incs highyield bond 
department lowells climbed with it and the brothers earned 
hundreds of millions of dollars 
now their fates are inextricably linked in the governments 
massive racketeering and fraud indictment which defense lawyers 
contend includes the other milken only to pressure michael into a 
settlement 
friends describe lowell milken as a devoted family man 
hardworking modest in taste and lifestyle despite his wealth 
devoted to running a charitable foundation formed four years before 
the government began probing drexel and the milkens 
lowell milken 40 looks nothing like his brother who stands 
over 6 feet tall wears black curly hair and has an angular face 
and narrow eyes lowell has straight sandy hair and is shorter 
and bespectacled both are described as sometimes abrasive at work 
like his brother lowell graduated from the university of 
california at berkeley in 1970 winning the business departments 
top student award that eluded michael two years earlier 
michael went east to the university of pennsylvanias wharton 
school but lowell attended the university of california at los 
angeles law school where he was an editor of the law review he 
joined the los angeles firm of irell amp manella where he is 
remembered as assiduous and creative in the fields of tax and 
corporate law 
but he left the firm in 1978 to join his brother at drexels 
highyield bond department in beverly hills calif where michael 
had moved the group from the investment firms new york 
headquarters 
while michael ran the xshaped trading desk lowell worked in an 
office on the other side of the floor michael won fame for 
reshaping american business through the issue of highyield 
