<TEXT>
a wall street stock promoter pleaded guilty 
friday to manipulating the prices of three overthecounter 
securities in the governments first fraud investigation emanating 
from the october 1987 market crash 
henry lorin 47 president of henlor securities capital ltd 
pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy to commit securities and 
mail fraud and obstructing an investigation by the securities and 
exchange commission 
he faces a maximum 10 years in prison and 500000 in fines a 
sentencing date was not set by us district judge thomas p griesa 
lorin also agreed to cooperate with the governments continuing 
investigation of haas securities corp a brokerage house that 
collapsed nine days after the oct 19 1987 stock market crash 
prosecutors maintain the firms alleged scheme to artificially 
raise the prices of penny stocks inexpensive securities traded 
over the counter couldnt be maintained after the market drop and 
share prices tumbled 
eugene laff former haas chairman was charged last month with 
15 counts of conspiring to mainipulate the prices of the same three 
stocks to increase their value in a scheme that included lorin 
both cases are based on the confessions of stanley a aslanian 
jr a former haas securities trader and president who pleaded 
guilty in january to conspiracy and agreed to cooperate with the 
government he has not been sentenced 
laff and aslanian were listed as coconspirators in the 
twocount criminal information to which lorin pleaded guilty 
lorin admitted to conspiring with laff and aslanian from july 
1986 until haas securities went out of business to manipulate the 
stock prices of flores de new mexico inc ts industries inc 
and big o tires inc 
the information states that the three through haas securities 
raised the stock prices at a time when sell orders exceeded buy 
orders and cornered the market on the stocks by accumulating 
hundreds of thousands of shares in haas inventories and setting 
artificially high prices 
i knew the prices were artificially high prices and helped to 
maintain the prices lorin told judge griesa 
laff and aslanian allegedly sought to create the appearance of 
demand for the three stock by selling some of the stock to accounts 
controlled by lorin listed in other peoples names 
the value of the deals and profits from the manipulations have 
not been listed in any court papers in the haas securities case 
lorin also admitted to giving false and misleading testimony to 
the sec in july 1987 when he denied placing stock orders for big o 
tires 
the investigation began when investors demanded information 
about the stocks after the crash haas securities allegedly was 
able to sustain the prices for several days after the crash until 
it filed for bankruptcy and the manipulated share prices plunged 
assistant us attorney bruce baird said the case was the first 
alleged fraud brought to light because of the crash 
the things haas was doing began before the crash but it was 
the crash that resulted in the downfall of haas and all these 
things came to life baird said 
