<TEXT>
sales of washington apples are returning to 
normal levels following the recent controversy over the use of the 
growthregulating chemical alar an industry official said friday 
outofstate apple shipments rose 18 percent in the past week 
to 141 million boxes from 119 million the week before said bill 
dewitt of the wenatchee valley traffic association 
thats approaching the 156 million boxes shipped the week of 
march 9 just before three consecutive weeks of sliding sales 
prompted by consumer fears last year at this time warehouses 
shipped 12 million boxes 
a report released by the natural resources defense council in 
late february indicated that eating apples treated with the alar 
increased cancer risk in children 
the report was denounced by the apple industry which said only 
about 5 percent of the crop is treated with the chemical and 
several federal agencies declared apples safe to eat 
an nrdc attorney who coauthored the alar report friday offered 
an olive branch to growers of the nations largest apple crop 
we want to make peace with growers janet hathaway of the 
washington dcbased environmental group said it would be very 
useful if growers started to see we are on the same side 
dewitt said exports were up 13000 boxes to 119000 shipped 
with 57000 of those sent to taiwan taiwan had been the most 
visible foreign market to drop washington apple imports after the 
controversy started 
apple shipments to retailers exporters and institutional users 
are considered an accurate measure of consumer sales 
i think fortunately the people have short memories and maybe 
they are coming back to buying apples said dewitt whose group 
collects shipment from washington warehouses gathered by state 
government 
people are beginning to realize that if there really was a 
problem theyd be taking them off the market like chilean 
grapes he said 
prices remain soft with the top grade of red delicious apples 
bringing just 11 to 12 per 42pound box 2 to 3 below the level 
prior to the alar flap and barely above the cost of production 
alar is the marketing name for daminozide which is mostly used 
on red apples to improve color firmness and increase shelf life 
its use still is legal but the federal environmental protection 
agency has proposed banning it next year 
