chicory with blanched leaves lettucelike texture and a tangy 
flavor 
thanks both to dukakis and the trendiness of exotic produce in 
general us sales shot up from 300 tons in 1981 to 3000 tons 
last year according to the marketing board 
at an average supermarket price of 2 to 3 a pound belgian 
endive sales total about 15 million a year but on a per capita 
basis americans are still microconsumers of the vegetable eating 
less than one ounce per person per year compared to 20 pounds per 
person in belgium 
belgians are also the dominant growers producing about 80 
percent of the worlds crop but scientists at the university of 
massachusetts at amherst are hoping to change that 
their research which began three years ago and has received 
170000 of funding from the us department of agriculture is 
aimed at developing new varieties and hydroponic or waterbased 
growing techniques it could turn a corner next year when farmers 
start growing experimental batches 
the chinese may not be far behind professor kenneth a corey 
who is supervising the research has two postdoctoral students 
from the peoples republic of china who are interested in taking 
the crop to their homeland 
for chefs belgian endives allure is that it does not fall 
apart in cooking farmers can charge top dollar because it requires 
a laborintensive growing process in which the white roots are 
harvested and then placed in pitchdark rooms to force the growth 
of the tender leaves 
